Let me build the full thing for the orders.js legacy case. The key idea is that there are three layers, and they cost different amounts of tokens:

- CLAUDE.md — loads every session, automatically. So it must be tiny. It holds only the hard law and a pointer.
- The ontology file — a small map. It does not hold knowledge; it says what notes exist, what each is for, and when to open it. Claude reads this to decide what else to load.
- The nest of notes — the actual knowledge. Each note is loaded only when the map says it is needed, never all at once.

That split is the whole token argument in advance: the always-on part stays small, and the heavy knowledge is pulled in slices on demand.

A folder structure is just where files sit. 
  An ontology is the model of the knowledge: the kinds of things that exist, what they mean, how they relate, 
  how they are written down, and what actions they trigger. The folder structure is one small output of the ontology
(the "representation" part). Here is both, fully, for the legacy orders.js case.

A. The folder structure

legacy/
├── CLAUDE.md                       ← always-loaded law (tiny: rule + pointer)
├── _ontology.md                    ← the knowledge model (the big file below)
├── INDEX.md                        ← flat list of every note, auto-maintained
│
├── knowledge/                      ← the nest; loaded one slice at a time
│   ├── style/                      ← entity type: StyleRule + CanonicalExample
│   │   ├── canonical-example.md
│   │   ├── naming.md
│   │   └── control-flow.md
│   ├── gotchas/                    ← entity type: Gotcha
│   │   ├── data-shapes.md
│   │   ├── db-singleton.md
│   │   └── type-coercion.md
│   ├── exceptions/                 ← entity type: Exception
│   │   ├── sql-placeholders.md
│   │   └── error-logging.md
│   └── decisions/                  ← entity type: Decision (the "why")
│       └── why-no-refactor.md
│
├── archive/                        ← superseded notes (read-only, kept for history)
│
└── src/                            ← entity type: CodeUnit (the governed code)
    ├── orders.js
    ├── customers.js
    └── invoices.js

The folders map one-to-one to the entity types the ontology defines. That is not a coincidence; the ontology decides what types exist, and the folders are where each type is stored.

B. The ontology

This is the file Claude reads to understand the domain, not just to find files. It has five parts: the entity types (what exists), the relationships (how they connect), the representations (how each is written down), the vocabulary (what terms mean), and the actions (what Claude must do and when).

# legacy/_ontology.md
## Knowledge model for the legacy module

This file defines what kinds of knowledge exist in this folder, what they mean,
how they relate, how they are written, and what Claude must do with them.
Read this before reading any note. It is the model; the notes are the data.

---

## 1. Entity types (the things that exist)

Six types of thing live in this knowledge base. Every note is exactly one type.

- **CodeUnit** — a function or file in `src/`. This is the thing being governed.
  It does not live in `knowledge/`; it is the subject the knowledge is about.

- **StyleRule** — a mandatory pattern that new CodeUnits must follow
  (e.g. "use var, not const"). Binding by default.

- **CanonicalExample** — a real, working snippet that demonstrates several
  StyleRules at once. The thing to imitate when in doubt.

- **Gotcha** — a fact about the real runtime behavior of the code that
  constrains how you may write it (e.g. "ids arrive as strings").

- **Exception** — an explicit, bounded permission to break a StyleRule, with a
  reason and a replacement pattern. Nothing may deviate without one.

- **Decision** — a recorded rationale for why the rules are what they are
  (e.g. "why we never refactor this"). Explains, does not command.

---

## 2. Relationships (how the types connect)

These are the typed links between entities. They define how the model holds
together, and they encode precedence.

    CodeUnit        --MUST-FOLLOW-->   StyleRule
    CanonicalExample --DEMONSTRATES--> StyleRule
    Gotcha          --CONSTRAINS-->    CodeUnit
    Exception       --OVERRIDES-->     StyleRule        (bounded, one rule each)
    Decision        --JUSTIFIES-->     StyleRule

Precedence axiom (the most important relationship):
    Exception > StyleRule.
    A StyleRule is binding UNLESS an Exception OVERRIDES it for this case.
    If no Exception applies, the StyleRule is absolute.

---

## 3. Representations (how each type is written down)

Each entity is one markdown note with frontmatter so Claude can read it without
guessing. The frontmatter is the machine-readable part; the body is the human
explanation.

Storage:
    StyleRule, CanonicalExample  -> knowledge/style/
    Gotcha                       -> knowledge/gotchas/
    Exception                    -> knowledge/exceptions/
    Decision                     -> knowledge/decisions/

Naming: kebab-case slug describing the fact (e.g. `type-coercion.md`).

Required frontmatter by type:

    # StyleRule
    ---
    type: StyleRule
    id: style.var-only
    statement: "Use var for all variables; never const or let."
    applies-to: all functions in src/
    demonstrated-by: style.canonical-example
    ---

    # Exception
    ---
    type: Exception
    id: exc.sql-placeholders
    overrides: style.string-sql
    scope: "any new database query"
    reason: "string-built SQL is an injection risk"
    replacement: 'db.query("... WHERE x = ?", [val], cb)'
    status: active
    ---

    # Gotcha
    ---
    type: Gotcha
    id: gotcha.ids-are-strings
    constrains: src/*.js
    fact: "ids arrive from the router as strings; SQL relies on DB coercion"
    ---

The `overrides`, `demonstrated-by`, and `constrains` fields ARE the relationships
from section 2, written so Claude can resolve them mechanically.

---

## 4. Controlled vocabulary (what the terms mean)

Fixed meanings, so the model does not drift:

- **Binding** — must be followed; no judgment allowed.
- **Bounded** — applies only within the stated `scope`, nowhere else.
- **Deviation** — any code that does not match a StyleRule. Forbidden unless an
  Exception authorizes it.
- **Match** — copy the CanonicalExample's pattern, not merely "be similar".
- "Maintenance mode" — we preserve existing style; quality is not the goal,
  consistency is.

---

## 5. Actions (what Claude does, and when)

These are the operational rules. They turn the model into behavior.

**LOAD actions (which notes to open for a task):**

    WHEN writing or editing a function
      -> read CLAUDE.md + knowledge/style/canonical-example.md
    WHEN touching data handling or the db
      -> also load the relevant knowledge/gotchas/*.md
    WHEN writing a query OR handling errors
      -> also load the relevant knowledge/exceptions/*.md
    NEVER load all notes at once. Load only the slice the task names.

**VALIDATE action (the anti-hallucination rule):**

    Before writing code, check each line against the StyleRules.
    IF a line deviates from a StyleRule
       AND no active Exception OVERRIDES that rule for this scope
    THEN the line is forbidden. Rewrite it to MATCH the CanonicalExample.
    Claude may not invent a "compromise" pattern. If unsure, copy the example.

**WRITE-KNOWLEDGE action (how a new fact enters the nest):**

    1. Classify the new fact as one of the six types.
    2. Write it to that type's folder with the required frontmatter.
    3. Add one row to INDEX.md.
    4. If it is an Exception, set `overrides` to the exact StyleRule id.
    IF the fact fits no existing type, STOP and add the new type to section 1
    before writing the note.

**LIFECYCLE action (how knowledge ages):**

    A note's status moves draft -> active -> superseded.
    A superseded note moves to archive/ and its INDEX row is struck through.
    Active notes are the only ones Claude obeys.

How the ontology earns its place over a plain folder map

A folder map only answers "where is the file." This ontology answers four more
things a folder cannot:

- What each note is (the six types and their meanings), so Claude treats an
Exception differently from a StyleRule instead of reading them as flat text.
- How they relate (Exception OVERRIDES StyleRule), so precedence is decided
by the model, not guessed in the moment. This is what stops the "made-up
compromise" hallucination: the conflict between good practice and existing
practice is resolved by a written rule, not by Claude's judgment.
- How they are written (frontmatter with overrides, constrains), so the
relationships are machine-readable and Claude can resolve them without reading
every body. That is the token win: it can check the frontmatter index, then
open only the one note it needs.
- What actions to take (LOAD, VALIDATE, WRITE, LIFECYCLE), so the knowledge
is not just stored, it drives behavior. The VALIDATE action in particular is
the rule that forbids any deviation not backed by an Exception, which is the
exact safeguard against Claude reverting to its trained "good practice."

So the folder structure is the body, and the ontology is the nervous system: it
says what the parts are, how they connect, how to read them, and what to do.

  
  
  
  
