1. What goes in CLAUDE.md (always loaded — keep it tiny)

# legacy/ — maintenance mode

This code is live and the customer depends on it. New code must MATCH the
existing style, not modern best practice. Consistency is the rule.

Hard rules:
- Match the style of orders.js exactly. Do not modernize.
- Before writing here, read `legacy/_ontology.md` and load only the note it
  points you to.

The one example to copy if you read nothing else:

    function getOrder(id, cb) {
      var sql = "SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id = " + id;
      db.query(sql, function(err, rows) { cb(rows[0]); });
    }

That is all. It is small on purpose, because you pay for it every session. It
gives the law and one example, then sends Claude to the map for anything deeper.

---
2. The ontology — the map Claude reads to know what to open

This is the file that makes the nest cheap. It is short, and it tells Claude
which single note to load for the task at hand so Claude never loads the whole
folder.

# legacy/_ontology.md — map of the legacy notes

Each note below holds one kind of knowledge. Load ONLY the note that matches
your task. Do not load all of them.

| Note | What it holds | Load it WHEN you are... |
|------|---------------|-------------------------|
| style-example.md   | One real function, annotated with every habit to copy | writing or editing any function here |
| gotchas.md         | Quirks that will bite you (data shapes, the shared db) | debugging, or touching data/db code |
| safe-exceptions.md | The few places we are allowed to deviate from old style | writing a query, or handling errors |

Rules for keeping this nest honest:
- A new fact goes into exactly one note above. If it fits none, add a new row
  here first, then the note.
- Style facts -> style-example.md. Traps -> gotchas.md. Allowed deviations ->
  safe-exceptions.md.
- Keep each note small. If a note grows past a screen, split it and add a row.

The "Load it WHEN" column is the important part. It is the routing rule that lets
Claude open one small note instead of reading the whole codebase to guess.

---
3. The nest — the actual knowledge notes

These are loaded one at a time, only when the map points to them.

style-example.md — the pattern, with every habit named so there is nothing left to guess:

# Style example — copy this exactly

    var db = require('./db');           // shared singleton, required at top

    function getOrder(id, cb) {         // last argument is always the callback
      var sql = "SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id = " + id;  // var, not const
      db.query(sql, function(err, rows) {                 // callback shape (err, rows)
        cb(rows[0]);                    // single-row fetchers return rows[0]
      });
    }

Habits to copy:
- `var` for every variable. Never const/let.
- Callbacks, never async/await or promises.
- The callback is always the last argument, named `cb`.
- No try/catch. No validation unless the old code already has it.
- One flat function. Do not split or add helpers.

gotchas.md — the traps, so Claude does not invent behavior that isn't there:

# Gotchas in legacy/

- `db` is a single shared connection required at the top of each file. Do NOT
  create a new connection or pool. Reuse the existing `db`.
- `db.query` always returns `rows` as an array. Single-row fetchers do `rows[0]`.
- `id` arrives from the router as a STRING. The old SQL relies on the database
  coercing it. Do not add Number() conversions; it changes behavior.
- There are no transactions anywhere. Do not introduce them.
- The old code ignores the `err` argument. See safe-exceptions.md before you
  decide whether to handle it.

safe-exceptions.md — the deviations that are explicitly allowed, so Claude is not left to judge them silently:

# Allowed deviations from old style

The old style is the default. These are the ONLY exceptions. Anything not
listed here must match the old code.

1. SQL placeholders are allowed (security).
   The old string-built SQL is an injection risk. New queries MAY use `?`:

       var sql = "SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = ?";
       db.query(sql, [customerId], function(err, rows) { cb(rows); });

2. You MAY log `err` if a query fails, but you must still call `cb` the old way.
   Do not throw, and do not change the callback shape.

If a deviation is not on this list, do not make it. Add it here first, with the
reason, then follow it.

---
4. How this saves tokens (even though it costs some each session)

Yes, CLAUDE.md and the ontology cost a small fixed amount every session. The
saving is in what they let you avoid. Compare the two ways of working.

Without the nest, every session:
- The dev re-types "keep the old style, don't modernize" in chat. Tokens spent, and usually said imperfectly, so Claude still has to guess the details.
- To figure out what "the old style" actually is, Claude reads several source files (orders.js, customers.js, invoices.js) and reverse-engineers the conventions. That is thousands of tokens of code, paid again every session, because nothing remembers the conclusion.
- If it guesses wrong, you get a round of rework. More tokens.

With the nest:
- CLAUDE.md is small and identical every session, so it sits in the prompt cache and is nearly free after the first load.
- The ontology tells Claude to open one small note (style-example.md) for the task, instead of scanning the whole folder. One short read replaces a codebase scan.
- The convention is written down once, so it is never re-derived. The answer is looked up, not recomputed.

So the trade is a small, cached, fixed cost in exchange for cutting the large, repeated cost of re-explaining and re-scanning. The ontology is the lever that makes it pay: without it, Claude would load every note and you would lose the saving. With it, Claude loads only the slice the task needs.

---
5. How this reduces hallucination (the good-vs-existing conflict)

Here is the actual conflict. Claude's training says "good practice": const,
async/await, validation, safe queries. This codebase says the opposite: var,
callbacks, no validation. When you give Claude a vague instruction or none, it
has to resolve that conflict by guessing, and guessing is where hallucination
comes from. It shows up in three ways:

1. Defaulting to training — it writes the modern version because that is its
strongest habit, ignoring the codebase.
2. Mixing styles — half old, half new, in one function, because it could not
decide.
3. Inventing a compromise — a pattern that exists nowhere: not the real old
style, and not a real best practice, just something it made up to satisfy both
pulls. This third one is the dangerous hallucination, because it looks
plausible and matches nothing.

A single chat line like "don't modernize" does not fix this,
style is, and may hallucinate that too.

The nest removes the guess by writing the resolution down:

- style-example.md gives a real artifact to copy, so there is no "what is
the old style?" to invent. Imitation replaces invention.
- safe-exceptions.md settles the security tension explicitly. Without it,
Claude silently decides whether to "fix" the unsafe SQL, and either choice can
be wrong. With it, the decision is already made, so there is no judgment call
left to get wrong.
- gotchas.md records the real behavior (ids are strings, db is shared), so
Claude does not fabricate behavior the code does not have.

In short: hallucination here is Claude filling a gap between two conflicting
pulls. The nest fills the gap with written ground truth, so there is no gap left
to fill with a guess. The model copies a real thing instead of inventing a
compromise, and the conflict that caused the hallucination is resolved on paper
before Claude ever sees it.
